\begin_layout Abstract
It is well understood that offspring can rely on different sources of maternal
 information, such as the maternal genotype (maternal genetic effects),
 the maternal phenotype (cascading maternal effects) or the maternal environment
 (maternal environmental effects).
 So far, studies on the evolution of maternal effects typically consider
 only one source of maternal information, raising the question whether conclusio
ns are robust to the type of maternal effect involved.
 To address this question, we develop a quantitative genetics approach which
 compares the evolutionary dynamics of different types of maternal effects
 in environments either characterized by i) a peak shift, or fluctuations
 that are either ii) deterministic or iii) stochastic.
 In the absence of constraints, maternal enviromental effects should be
 the most common type of maternal effect.
 This is because the maternal environment provides a direct source of informatio
n about the offspring's environment (at least when environments are autocorrelat
ed).
 By contrast, maternal genetic effects and cascading maternal effects only
 provide indirect sources of information about the environment through the
 maternal phenotype, requiring not only a environmental autocorrelation,
 but also a correlation between the maternal genotype or phenotype and her
 environment.
 Moreover, the evolution of some maternal genetic effects depends strongly
 on the type of environmental change: upon a peak shift, strong and positive
 maternal genetic effects are selectively favored, whereas a fluctuating
 environment selects against maternal genetic effects.
 We conclude that evolutionary dynamics diverge considerably dependent on
 the type of maternal effect involved.
\end_layout

