\begin_layout Standard
The current model builds on the seminal quantitative genetics model of maternal
 effects by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kirkpatrick1989"

\end_inset

 (see also 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "Lande1990,Hoyle2012"

\end_inset

), which considers consequences of an evolutionarily constant maternal effect
 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 to adaptation.
 Recently, we have extended this study by allowing for the evolution of
 this cascading maternal effect and to assess its interaction with within-genera
tional phenotypic plasticity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kuijper2015"

\end_inset

.
 Here, we take this analysis one step further by not only considering the
 evolution of cascading maternal effects, but also the evolution of maternal
 genetic effects and maternal environmental effects.
 To assess when and where these three different types of maternal effect
 are likely to affect the evolutionary process, it is essential to consider
 the evolution of alternative modes of adaptation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Botero2015"

\end_inset

.
 To this end, we consider how these three different types of maternal effects
 interact with evolving within-generational plasticity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lande2009,Chevin2010a,Tufto2015"

\end_inset

, by means of linear reaction norm with elevation 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{t}$
\end_inset

 and slope 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cascading maternal effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we provide a brief recap of the model on cascading maternal effects
 as considered in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kuijper2015"

\end_inset

.
 An individual's phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z_{t}=a_{t}+b_{t}\varepsilon_{t-\tau}+m_{t}z_{t-1}^{*}+e_{t},\label{eq:cascading:phenotype}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the elevation of the genotypic reaction norm in the reference environment
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t-\tau}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the genetically encoded slope of the reaction norm that determines a
 within-generational response to environment 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t-\tau}$
\end_inset

, whose influence is felt a fraction of time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 of a generation before selection 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lande2009"

\end_inset

.
 Next, 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the cascading maternal effect coefficient that reflects a linear, transgener
ational reaction norm on the parental 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t-1}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $*$
\end_inset

 reflects the notion that maternal phenotypes are measured after survival
 selection, which is assumed to take place prior to reproduction.
 Finally, 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the residual component of variation.
 The population is assumed to reproduce sexually and generations are non-overlap
ping.
 Selection on parents is assumed to occur through mortality selection.
 Individual-based simulations show, however, that identical results hold
 in the presence of fecundity selection.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Calculations for the evolution of cascading maternal effects are presented
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kuijper2015"

\end_inset

 and we restate here for convenience the bare bones.
 We define individual fitness as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W=W_{{\rm max}}\exp\left[-\frac{\left(z_{t}-\theta_{t}\right){}^{2}}{2\omega_{z}^{2}}-\frac{b_{t}^{2}}{2\omega_{b}^{2}}-\frac{m_{t}^{2}}{2\omega_{m}^{2}}\right],\label{eq:cascading:fitness}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{t}=A+B\varepsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the optimum phenotype at selection in generation 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and is a linear function of the environmental variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are constants that respectively determine the intercept and amplitude of
 fluctuations in the selective optimum.
 The constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{z}$
\end_inset

 is an inverse measure of the strength of selection, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{m}$
\end_inset

 are inverse measures of the costs of plasticity and maternal effects respective
ly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The updates in the population means of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 at selection are given to leading order in 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\omega^{2}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Delta\bar{a}_{t} & =-\frac{G_{aa}}{\omega_{z}^{2}}\left[\left(\bar{z}_{t}-\theta_{t}\right)\frac{\partial\bar{z}_{t}}{\partial\bar{a}_{t}}+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial\sigma_{z_{t}}^{2}}{\partial\bar{a}_{t}}\right],\label{deltaa}\\
\Delta\bar{b}_{t} & =-\frac{G_{bb}}{\omega_{z}^{2}}\left[\left(\bar{z}_{t}-\theta_{t}\right)\frac{\partial\bar{z}_{t}}{\partial\bar{b}_{t}}+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial\sigma_{z_{t}}^{2}}{\partial\bar{b}_{t}}+\frac{\omega_{z}^{2}\bar{b}_{t}}{\omega_{b}^{2}}\right],\label{deltab}\\
\Delta\bar{m}_{t} & =-\frac{G_{mm}}{\omega_{z}^{2}}\left[\left(\bar{z}_{t}-\theta_{t}\right)\frac{\partial\bar{z}_{t}}{\partial\bar{m}_{t}}+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial\sigma_{z_{t}}^{2}}{\partial\bar{m}_{t}}+\frac{\omega_{z}^{2}\bar{m}_{t}}{\omega_{m}^{2}}\right].\label{deltam}
\end{align}

\end_inset

In what follows, we assume as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kuijper2015"

\end_inset

 did that the covariances 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{ab}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{am}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{bm}$
\end_inset

 are all zero, i.e.
 that no two of the additive genetic effect, slope of plasticity and maternal
 effect coefficient covary.
 We note however that individual-based simulations, in which covariances
 are free to evolve, yield nearly identical results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will now use the expressions above to derive update rules for evolution
 under two alternative models of maternal effects - maternal-environmental
 and maternal-genetic - and compare the response of the three mechanisms
 to different patterns of environmental change.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Maternal environmental effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case, the individual's phenotype is sensitive not to the phenotype
 of its mother, but to the environment the mother experienced during her
 window of sensitivity, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t-1-\tau}$
\end_inset

.
 An individual's phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is therefore now given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z_{t}=a_{t}+b_{t}\varepsilon_{t-\tau}+m_{t}\varepsilon_{t-1-\tau}+e_{t}.\label{eq:environmental:phenotype}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The population mean phenotype and the phenotypic variance in generation
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 are thus given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\bar{z}_{t} & =\bar{a}_{t}+\bar{b}_{t}\varepsilon_{t-\tau}+\bar{m}_{t}\epsilon_{t-1-\tau},\label{eq:environmental:mean_phenotype}\\
\sigma_{z_{t}}^{2} & =G_{aa}+G_{bb}\varepsilon_{t-\tau}^{2}+G_{mm}\varepsilon_{t-1-\tau}^{2}+\sigma_{e}^{2}.\label{eq:environmental:phenotypic_variance}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & \frac{\partial\sigma_{z_{t}}^{2}}{\partial\bar{a}_{t}}=\frac{\partial\sigma_{z_{t}}^{2}}{\partial\bar{b}_{t}}=\frac{\partial\sigma_{z_{t}}^{2}}{\partial\bar{m}_{t}}=0,\\
 & \frac{\partial\bar{z}_{t}}{\partial\bar{a}_{t}}=1,\quad\frac{\partial\bar{z}_{t}}{\partial\bar{b}_{t}}=\varepsilon_{t-\tau},\quad\frac{\partial\bar{z}_{t}}{\partial\bar{m}_{t}}=\varepsilon_{t-1-\tau},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so the evolutionary change in the reaction norm and the maternal environment
al effect at generation 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Delta\bar{a}_{t} & =-\frac{G_{aa}}{\omega_{z}^{2}}(\bar{z}_{t}-\theta_{t}),\\
\Delta\bar{b}_{t} & =-\frac{G_{bb}}{\omega_{z}^{2}}\left[(\bar{z}_{t}-\theta_{t})\varepsilon_{t-\tau}+\frac{\omega_{z}^{2}\bar{b}_{t}}{\omega_{b}^{2}}\right],\\
\Delta\bar{m}_{t} & =-\frac{G_{mm}}{\omega_{z}^{2}}\left[(\bar{z}_{t}-\theta_{t})\varepsilon_{t-1-\tau}+\frac{\omega_{z}^{2}\bar{m}_{t}}{\omega_{m}^{2}}\right].
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Maternal genetic effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this third model the offspring phenotype is sensitive to its mother's
 genotype through an indirect maternal effects pathway in addition to the
 direct genetic pathway from the mother: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{t}=a_{t}+b_{t}\epsilon_{t-\tau}+m_{t}a_{t-1}^{*}+e_{t}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have mean phenotype and phenotypic variation given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bar{z}_{t} & =\bar{a}_{t}+\bar{b}_{t}\epsilon_{t-\tau}+\bar{m}_{t}\bar{a}_{t-1}^{*},\\
 & \approx\bar{a}_{t}+\bar{b}_{t}\epsilon_{t-\tau}+\bar{m}_{t}\bar{a}_{t},\\
\sigma_{z_{t}}^{2} & =G_{aa}+G_{bb}\epsilon_{t-\tau}^{2}+2\bar{m}_{t}C_{a_{t}a_{t-1}^{*}}+\overline{m_{t}^{2}(a_{t-1}^{*})^{2}}-\bar{m}_{t}^{2}(\bar{a}_{t-1}^{*})^{2}+\sigma_{e}^{2},\\
 & \approx G_{aa}(1+\bar{m}_{t}+\bar{m}_{t}^{2}+G_{mm})+G_{bb}\epsilon_{t-\tau}^{2}+G_{mm}\bar{a}_{t}^{2}+\sigma_{e}^{2},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we have approximated 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a_{t}a_{t-1}^{*}}\approx G_{aa}/2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{a_{t-1}^{*}a_{t-1}^{*}}\approx G_{aa}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}_{t-1}^{*}\approx\bar{a}_{t}$
\end_inset

 (weak selection).
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & \frac{\partial\sigma_{z_{t}}^{2}}{\partial\bar{a}_{t}}=2G_{mm}\bar{a}_{t},\quad\frac{\partial\sigma_{z_{t}}^{2}}{\partial\bar{b}_{t}}=0,\quad\frac{\partial\sigma_{z_{t}}^{2}}{\partial\bar{m}_{t}}=G_{aa}(1+2\bar{m}_{t}),\\
 & \frac{\partial\bar{z}_{t}}{\partial\bar{a}_{t}}=1+\bar{m}_{t},\quad\frac{\partial\bar{z}_{t}}{\partial\bar{b}_{t}}=\epsilon_{t-\tau},\quad\frac{\partial\bar{z}_{t}}{\partial\bar{m}_{t}}=\bar{a}_{t},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so the updates under selection at generation 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Delta\bar{a}_{t} & =-\frac{G_{aa}}{\omega_{z}^{2}}\left[(\bar{z}_{t}-\theta_{t})(1+\bar{m_{t}})+G_{mm}\bar{a}_{t}\right],\\
\Delta\bar{b}_{t} & =-\frac{G_{bb}}{\omega_{z}^{2}}\left[(\bar{z}_{t}-\theta_{t})\epsilon_{t-\tau}+\frac{\omega_{z}^{2}\bar{b}_{t}}{\omega_{b}^{2}}\right],\\
\Delta\bar{m}_{t} & =-\frac{G_{mm}}{\omega_{z}^{2}}\left[(\bar{z}_{t}-\theta_{t})\bar{a}_{t}+\frac{1}{2}G_{aa}(1+2\bar{m}_{t})+\frac{\omega_{z}^{2}\bar{m}_{t}}{\omega_{m}^{2}}\right].
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

